<HEADLINE>
FT  23 AUG 93 / Conservative rebels predict rail bill defeat
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS and KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TORY REBELS claimed yesterday that the government faces an embarrassing
Commons defeat over rail privatisation if British Rail goes ahead with
planned fare increases of up to 16 per cent.
According to leaked Network SouthEast documents British Rail's 'preferred
option' for meeting its expected revenue shortfall is to raise the price of
Travelcards by 16.2 per cent, single tickets by 12 per cent and season
tickets by 7.9 per cent.
The figures are among three alternatives which will go before the BR board
next month.
The leaked documents will stiffen the resolve of Conservative backbench
rebels to force concessions from the government when the privatisation bill
returns to the Commons in the autumn.
Their chance will come when MPs vote on a Lords amendment which would allow
BR to bid against private companies for franchises to operate trains after
privatisation.
The government is determined to reverse the amendment, which was proposed by
Lord Peyton, a former Conservative transport minister.
Downing Street claims the amendment in effect wrecks the bill. A leading
rebel said yesterday, however, that 'a large number' of backbenchers were
willing to defy the government.
He said: 'These are not the wild men who are always voting against the
government, these are loyal Tory MPs who cannot accept what the government
is trying to do.'
Another rebel, Mr Andrew Bowden (Brighton Kemptown), said price rises on the
scale proposed would go down 'like a lead balloon' with his constituents.
'I think it is quite unreasonable for fare increases to be excessive. I
think it's just speculation, but if it did go ahead I would make very strong
protests to the secretary of state,' he said.
Sir Keith Speed (Ashford), said there would be 'a political storm' if the
government approved fare increases of 16 per cent when inflation stood at
just over 1 per cent.
'My constituents have the worst service in Network SouthEast. There is no
way I could see them paying 16 per cent increases in fares,' he said.
Mr Michael Patterson, secretary of the Central Transport Consultative
Committee, the BR watchdog, said passengers 'would prefer a hole in the head
to fare increases of 16 per cent'.
Mr Brian Wilson, Labour's transport spokesman, said the leaked documents
provided evidence that the government would have to abandon privatisation.
'They cannot simply blunder on in the full knowledge that the huge costs
involved in privatising and fragmenting the network are destined to be paid
for by the travelling public,' he said.
Neither the Department of Transport nor British Rail would comment on the
documents, or on reports that rural lines - including those on the Isle of
Wight and between Shrewsbury and Aberystwyth - are set to suffer cuts in
Sunday services.
</TEXT>
<XX>
